# Seedance 2 References

- Default video model is `seedance2`.
- Runway Seedance 2 accepts only **integer** clip lengths from **5** to **15** seconds inclusive. Never write a smaller `durationTarget` or a fractional value for segments synced to Recipe2Video.
- Default output ratio is `1080:1920` for 9:16 vertical 1080p.
- Product-side cost estimate is 40 credits per second.
- Use Seedance References mode as the primary workflow.
- Do not use first/last keyframes as the production pattern.
- If an image must act as start or target state, pass it as a named reference and state its role explicitly in the prompt.
- Each segment must stay within 9 image inputs total.
- Every segment needs a kitchen continuity pair:
  - `@KitchenLayoutContextWide` as structural kitchen context;
  - one shot-specific kitchen view (`@KitchenIslandDefault`, `@KitchenIslandOverhead`, `@InductionWide`, `@OvenWide`, etc.).
- Do not force `@KitchenIslandDefault` when another kitchen angle is the shot view; use it when it is the active framing or when explicit terrazzo lock is needed.
- Every reference in a prompt must state its role exactly.
- If the 9-image limit is hit, remove expression/pose niceties before removing kitchen identity or critical food-state references.
- For ambiguous food shapes, lock scale explicitly (size range + relative anchor + count when visible).
- Add negative scale constraints for known drift risks (`not oversized`, `not miniature`).
- Keep proportion continuity across adjacent segments by restating the same scale lock in each related prompt.
- Keep kitchen material continuity across adjacent segments (no countertop/stovetop redesign drift).
- Use task-correct utensils when available in assets (no near-miss substitutions).
- Avoid cloth-in-hand hot-transfer prompts due hand/cloth fusion risk.

## Prompt Shape

Seedance prompts should be concise English prompts with:

- reference roles;
- exact number of shots;
- total duration;
- hard cuts;
- mandatory timing;
- integrated ASMR audio;
- short negatives;
- no speech;
- no voiceover;
- no music;
- no text on screen;
- no extra shots.
- include scale locks when relevant.
- include kitchen continuity locks when relevant.

## Fragile Food States

Use state references for transformations Seedance is likely to misread:

- choux puffing;
- pastry lamination;
- rising dough;
- brittle caramel;
- glazing;
- cracking crust;
- repeated crowns or rosettes;
- filled/cut/final geometry.

For complex transformations, prefer short hard cuts between state references instead of asking Seedance to invent the full transformation.

## Recipe-Specific Reference Conditioning

Recipe-specific reference images (every entry in `reference-plan.json` with `source: "generated_reference_needed"`) are produced by GPT-Image 2 inside the Recipe2Video app. They are NOT free-form text-to-image: the app forwards a list of library globals as `referenceImages[]` so the model grounds the dish on the same kitchen, pan, and utensil it will reuse across Seedance segments.

- Every such entry MUST declare a `conditioningReferences: ["@Tag", ...]` array. Use the same `@Tag` form as Seedance prompts.
- Minimum coverage: one kitchen view (`KitchenIslandDefault` or the appropriate overhead/induction/oven variant) + the cookware (`baking_dish`, `SaucepanLarge`, etc.) + the dominant utensil when visible.
- NEVER include character-class anchors (`@CharacterSheet`, character poses, `@CharacterExpressions`). The app drops them at generation time because the mascot pollutes dish frames; the kitchen alone carries the Licorn visual identity for recipe-state images.
- Do not list the entry's own `canonicalName` in its `conditioningReferences`. Library canonical names only.
- Library globals (entries whose `canonicalName` already matches an `asset_library` row) do NOT need `conditioningReferences` — they are not GPT-Image 2 generated.

See `contracts/reference-image-generation.md` for the full policy and a worked example.
